state.title: Procedure to Register and Submit an Application

label.string: You must have legal status inside Canada at the time of application and must maintain it until the time of nomination. You are authorized to enter and remain in Canada as a temporary resident for a specific period of time, either as a visitor, worker or student. You must be in possession of a valid visitor record, work permit or study permit, or be a visa-exempt foreign national. If your visitor record, work permit, study permit has expired, you may still apply to the OINP if you have submitted an application to Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) to renew/extend your temporary status document before its expiry date.

label.text: This Stream is based on Work Experience obtained in Canada

state.title: Document Checklist to File an Application
Submitting an Application and Checking Application Status

label.string: Candidates who have obtained atleast 12 months of skilled work experience in Canada (30 hours/Week and total of 1560 hours per year), in the last three years (before you apply). The work must be Full-Time or equivalent hours of Part-Time. The work experience must have been obtained with proper work authorization.

label.text: The job must lie within NOC (O, A and B) catagory.
If you don't show your experience meets the experience in the NOC, your application will not be accepted

label.string: Candidate must have taken the International English Language Testing System: (IELTS-General Training) or Candian English Language Proficiency Index Program: (CELPIP-General Test) within the last two years of submitting the express entry application.

label.text: French Language Proficiency test includes: TEF (Test d’évaluation de français)

state.title: View Detailed Information on Language Requirement

label.string: There is No Education Requirement for Canadian Experience Class. However, you can earn points for education obtained from a Canadian Secondary or Post Secondary Institution.

You have foreign education and show a Education Credential Assesment (ECA) report from an approved agency showing that your foreign education is equal to a complete certificate, diploma or degree from a Canadian Secondary or Post Secondary School.

The person who is invited to apply and submits an application is the “principal applicant.” If you're married or live with a common-law foreign national partner in Canada, and that person also meets the requirements, either or both of you can fill out an Express Entry profile.
A common-law partner is a person who has lived with you in a marriage-like relationship for at least one year. Common-law partner refers to both opposite-sex and same-sex couples.
You must be admissible into Canada.

You have foreign education and show a Education Credential Assesment (ECA) report from an approved agency showing that your foreign education is equal to a complete certificate, diploma or degree from a Canadian Secondary or Post Secondary School.

The person who is invited to apply and submits an application is the “principal applicant.” If you're married or live with a common-law partner and that person also meets the requirements, either or both of you can fill out an Express Entry profile.
